Fair-skinned individuals can get enough vitamin D in 10-15 minutes of noontime sun exposure, while darker-skinned people may need up to 25 minutes.
Taking 2,000 IU of vitamin D3 daily and spending time in the sun can reduce cancer risk.
Studies show higher vitamin D levels correlate with lower cancer rates.
Experts recommend 1,000 IU of vitamin D daily for cancer prevention.
Sunlight exposure helps the body produce vitamin D, reducing breast cancer risk.
Increasing vitamin D intake from diet and supplements may be the safest way to maintain adequate levels.
